ewspaper= Latimes.com |date= 13 October 2009 |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[William Carlos Williams]]''' (Puerto Rican mother), [[Modernist]] poet<ref>Colgan, Richard (2009)  ''Advice to the Young Physician: On the Art of Medicine''. Springer Press.  p120</ref>\n* '''[[Emanuel Xavier]]''' (Puerto Rican father), poet and novelist<ref name=identity/>\n* '''[[Iris Zavala]]''' (born 1936), author, scholar, poet<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barcelonareview.com/41/s_iz_ent.htm |title=En El Mundo De Iris. Entrevista A Iris Zavala Por Domingo Luis Hern\u00e1ndez |publisher=Barcelonareview.com |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n* '''[[Manuel Zeno Gand\u00eda]]''', writer<br />''Zeno Gand\u00eda wrote'' La Charca, ''a notable late nineteenth-century Puerto Rican novel.''<ref name=\"Charca\">{{cite web|url=http://ponce.inter.edu/cai/bv/Charca.htm |title=La Charca, de Manuel Zeno Gand\u00eda: Pathfinder |publisher=Ponce.inter.edu |date= |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Literature}}\n* [[Before Columbus Foundation]]\n* [[History of women in Puerto Rico]]\n* [[List of Latin American writers]]\n* [[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n* [[Multi-Ethnic Literature of the United States]]\n* [[Puerto Rican literature]]\n* [[Media of Puerto Rico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=Torres>listed in V\u00edctor Federico Torres, ''Diccionario de autores puertorrique\u00f1os contempor\u00e1neos'', Plaza Mayor, 2009.</ref>\n<ref name=\"ENDI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zonai.com/promociones/biografias/1201/blanco.asp |accessdate=14 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927073549/http://www.zonai.com/promociones/biografias/1201/blanco.asp |archivedate=27 September 2011 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ND\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zonai.com/promociones/biografias/0101/josecampeche.asp |accessdate=7 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927074034/http://www.zonai.com/promociones/biografias/0101/josecampeche.asp |archivedate=27 September 2011 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Writers from Puerto Rico}}\n*Acosta-Bel\u00e9n, Edna. \"Puerto Rican Literature in the United States,\" in ''Redefining American Literary History'', Ed. A. LaVonne Brown Ruoff and Jerry W. Ward, MLA, 1990.\n*Aldama, Frederick. ''Routledge Concise History of Latino/a Literature,'' featuring Puerto Rican authors Miguel Algar\u00edn, Giannina Braschi, Pedro Pietri, Miguel Pi\u00f1ero, Esmeralda Santiago, Piri Thomas, et al., Routledge, 2013.\n*''[http://www1.uprh.edu/zjimenez/GENERACION80/bibliografia.htm Bibliograf\u00eda de escritores puertorrique\u00f1os de la Generaci\u00f3n Ochenta (Generation of the 80's)]''.\n*Cancel, Mario R. ''Literatura y narrativa puertorrique\u00f1a: la escritura entre siglos''. San Juan: Pasadizo, 2007.\n*Callahan, Laura. ''Spanish/English Codeswitching in a Written Corpus.'' John Benjamins Publishing, 2004. \n*Castillo, Debra. ''Redreaming America: Toward a Bilingual American Culture.'' On Ana Lydia Vega and Giannina Braschi. SUNY Series in Latin American and Iberian Thought and Culture, 2005. \n*L\u00f3pez Baralt, Mercedes. ''Literatura Puertorrique\u00f1a del Siglo XX:  Antolog\u00eda''. San Juan: EDUPR, 2004.\n*Mart\u00ednez M\u00e1rquez, Alberto, and Mario Cancel. ''El l\u00edmite volcado.  Antolog\u00eda de la Generaci\u00f3n de Poetas de los Ochenta''.  San Juan:  Isla Negra, 2000.\n* Milligan, Bryce, ''Floricanto S\u00ed!: A Collection of Latina Poetry.'' Penguin, 1998.\n*Moreira, Rub\u00e9n Alejandro. ''Antolog\u00eda de la poes\u00eda puertorrique\u00f1a. Vol. I Romanticismo; Vol.II Modernismo y Postmodernismo; Vol. III Contempor\u00e1nea; Vol. IV Contempor\u00e1nea''. San Juan: Tr\u00edptico, 1992-1993.\n*Ortega, Julio. ''Antolog\u00eda de la poes\u00eda latinoamericana del siglo XXI: el turno y la transici\u00f3n''. M\u00e9xico: Editorial Siglo XXI, 1997.\n*Torres, Lourdes. \"In the Contact Zone: Code-Switching Strategies by Latino/a Writers\", JUSTOR, 2007.\n*Stanchich, Maritza. \"Insular Interventions: Diasporic Puerto Rican Literature Bilanguaging toward a Greater Puerto Rico.\" Ph.D. diss, University of California, Santa Cruz, 2003.\n*Torres-Padilla, Jos\u00e9 L. and Carmen Hayd\u00e9e Rivera. ''Writing Off the Hyphen: New Critical Perspectives on the Literature of the Puerto Rican Diaspora.'' University of Washington Press, 2008. \n*Williams, Raymond L. ''The Columbia Guide to the Latin American Novel Since 1945.'' Featuring Puerto Rican novelists Giannina Braschi, Edgardo Rodr\u00edguez Juli\u00e1, Luis Rafael Sanchez, and Esmeralda Santiago. New york: Columbia University Press, 2007.\n*Zimmerman, Marc. ''U.S. Latino Literature: An Essay and Annotated Bibliography.'' MARCH/Abrazo, 1992.\n\n{{Lists of writers by nationality}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Puerto Rican Writers}}\n[[Category:Puerto Rican writers| List]]\n[[Category:Lists of Puerto Rican people by occupation|Writers]]\n[[Category:Lists of writers by nationality|Puerto Rican]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American writers| List]]\n[[Category:Lists of American writers|Puerto]]\n", "name_user": "Lawrlafo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eR\u2013S:Moved Segarra B\u00e1ez here.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Puerto_Rican_writers"}
{"title_page": "Mark Thurston", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|1=Biographies|date=January 2018}}\n{{Orphan|date=July 2017}}\n}}\n\n'''Mark John Thurston''' (born 3 January 1967)<ref>[https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/fOYokW35MOigViLmyX_i8NBwlMc/appointments Companies House]</ref> is a British electrical engineer and businessman, and the chief executive of proposed new and controversial railway project [[High Speed 2]] since March 2017.\n\n==Early life==\nThurston was born in the [[London Borough of Sutton]]. He has a younger brother (born 1969).\n\nFrom the [[College of North West London]] in 1983\u20131987 he gained a [[Higher National Certificate]] in Electrical and Electronic Engineering. He attended [[Loughborough University]] from 1999 to 2001 gaining an MSc in Engineering Management.\n\n==Career==\nThurston began his career as an apprentice with [[Transport for London]].<ref>[http://www.nottinghampost.com/mark-thurston-will-be-man-responsible-for-bringing-hs2-to-nottinghamshire/story-30088824-detail/story.html Nottingham Post January 2017]</ref> He later worked for [[Metronet]]. In June 2008, he joined [[CH2M Hill|CH2M]] as head of structures, bridges and highways.<ref>[https://www.ch2m.com/node/15021 CH2M]</ref> On 26 January 2017, Thurston was appointed chief executive of [[High Speed 2]].<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/news/hs2-announces-new-ceo Appointment]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThurston lives in [[Coulsdon]], Surrey. He married Amanda Warrilow in April 1994. They have two daughters (born June 1996 and October 1998).\n\n==See also==\n* Sir [[David Higgins (businessman)|David Higgins]], Chairman of HS2\n* [[High-speed rail in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.gov.uk/government/people/mark-thurston Biography]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-bus}}\n{{S-bef|before= Simon Kirby }}\n{{S-ttl|title= Chief Executive of [[High Speed 2]]|years= March 2017 - }}\n{{S-aft|after= Incumbent }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thurston, Mark}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Loughborough University]]\n[[Category:British rail transport chief executives]]\n[[Category:High Speed 2]]\n[[Category:People from Coulsdon]]\n[[Category:People from the London Borough of Sutton]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|1=Biographies|date=January 2018}}\n{{Orphan|date=July 2017}}\n}}\n\n'''Mark John Thurston''' (born 3 January 1967)<ref>[https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/fOYokW35MOigViLmyX_i8NBwlMc/appointments Companies House]</ref> is a British electrical engineer and businessman, and the Chief Executive of proposed new and controversial railway project [[High Speed 2]] since March 2017.\n\n==Early life==\nThurston was born in the [[London Borough of Sutton]]. He has a younger brother (born 1969).\n\nFrom the [[College of North West London]] in 1983\u20131987 he gained a [[Higher National Certificate]] in Electrical and Electronic Engineering. He attended [[Loughborough University]] from 1999 to 2001 gaining an MSc in Engineering Management.\n\n==Career==\nThurston began his career as an apprentice with [[Transport for London]].<ref>[http://www.nottinghampost.com/mark-thurston-will-be-man-responsible-for-bringing-hs2-to-nottinghamshire/story-30088824-detail/story.html Nottingham Post January 2017]</ref> He later worked for [[Metronet]]. In June 2008, he joined [[CH2M Hill|CH2M]] as head of structures, bridges and highways.<ref>[https://www.ch2m.com/node/15021 CH2M]</ref> On 26 January 2017, Thurston was appointed chief executive of [[High Speed 2]].<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/news/hs2-announces-new-ceo Appointment]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThurston lives in [[Coulsdon]], Surrey. He married Amanda Warrilow in April 1994. They have two daughters (born June 1996 and October 1998).\n\n==See also==\n* Sir [[David Higgins (businessman)|David Higgins]], Chairman of HS2\n* [[High-speed rail in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.gov.uk/government/people/mark-thurston Biography]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-bus}}\n{{S-bef|before= Simon Kirby }}\n{{S-ttl|title= Chief Executive of [[High Speed 2]]|years= March 2017 - }}\n{{S-aft|after= Incumbent }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thurston, Mark}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Loughborough University]]\n[[Category:British rail transport chief executives]]\n[[Category:High Speed 2]]\n[[Category:People from Coulsdon]]\n[[Category:People from the London Borough of Sutton]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Eagleash", "label": "safe", "comment": "caps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Thurston"}
{"title_page": "Google Penguin", "text_new": "{{short description|Google search engine algorithm update}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2014}}\n'''Google Penguin''' is a [[codename]]<ref name=SEL>{{cite web|author=Matt Cutts |url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/206232437427154944 |title=Penguin Gets Official Name |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref> for a Google algorithm update that was first announced on April 24, 2012. The update was aimed at decreasing [[Search engine optimization|search engine rankings]] of websites that violate Google's Webmaster Guidelines<ref>{{cite web|url=https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/35769#3|title=Webmaster Guidelines - Webmaster Tools Help|publisher=Support.google.com|accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref> by using now declared [[black-hat SEO]] techniques involved in increasing artificially the ranking of a webpage by manipulating the number of links pointing to the page. Such tactics are commonly described as link schemes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://support.google.com/webmasters/bin/answer.py?answer=66356 |title=Link schemes - Webmaster Tools Help |publisher=Support.google.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref> According to Google's John Mueller,<ref name=\"SEL\" /> Google has announced all updates to the Penguin filter to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://searchengineland.com/no-google-hasnt-released-unannounced-peguin-updates-149156|title=No, Google Hasn't Released Unannounced Penguin Updates|author=Barry Schwartz|date=February 20, 2013|accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Effect on search results==\nBy Google's estimates,<ref name=GBlog>http://insidesearch.blogspot.com/2012/04/another-step-to-reward-high-quality.html</ref> Penguin affects approximately 3.1% of [[Web search query|search queries]] in [[English language|English]], about 3% of queries in languages like [[German language|German]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], and [[Arabic]], and an even greater percentage of them in \"highly spammed\" languages. On May 25, 2012, Google unveiled another Penguin update, called Penguin 1.1. This update, according to [[Matt Cutts]], former head of webspam at Google, was supposed to affect less than one-tenth of a percent of English searches. The guiding principle for the update was to penalize websites that were using manipulative techniques to achieve high rankings. Pre-Penguin sites commonly used negative link building techniques to rank highly and get traffic, once Penguin was rolled out it meant that content was key and those with great content would be recognised and those with little or spammy content would be penalised and receive no ranking benefits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weareinfront.com/google-penguin-update-guide/|title=A Guide To The Penguin Update - In Front Digital|date=2015-03-12|website=In Front Digital|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref> The purpose per Google was to catch excessive spammers. Allegedly, few websites lost search rankings on Google for specific keywords during the [[Google Panda|Panda]] and Penguin rollouts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seroundtable.com/penguin-traffic-drop-chart-15096.html|title=Here Is What It Looks Like To Be Hit By Google Penguin|website=seroundtable.com|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref> Google specifically mentions that [[doorway page]]s, which are only built to attract search engine traffic, are against their webmaster guidelines.\n\nIn January 2012, the so-called Page Layout Algorithm Update<ref>{{cite web|url=http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2012/01/page-layout-algorithm-improvement.html |title=Official Google Webmaster Central Blog: Page layout algorithm improvement |publisher=Googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com |date=2012-01-19 |accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref> (also known as the Top Heavy Update)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://searchengineland.com/google-updates-page-layout-algorithm-go-sites-top-heavy-ads-183929|title=Google Updates Its Page Layout Algorithm To Go After Sites \"Top Heavy\" With Ads|date=February 10, 2014|publisher=SearchEngineLand.com|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> was released, which targeted websites with too many ads, or too little content [[above the fold]].\n\nPenguin 3 was released October 5, 2012 and affected 0.3% of queries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/254335294063656960 |title=Google Penguin Update 3 Released, Impacts 0.3% Of English-Language Queries |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=October 5, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2013}}</ref> Penguin 4 (also known as Penguin 2.0) was released on May 22, 2013 and affected 2.3% of queries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mattcutts.com/blog/penguin-2-0-rolled-out-today/ |title=Penguin 4, With Penguin 2.0 Generation Spam-Fighting |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=May 22, 2013 |accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> Penguin 5 (also known as Penguin 2.1)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/386231794883780609 |title=The Penguin 2.1 Spam-Filtering Algorithm |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=October 4, 2013 |accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> was released on October 4, 2013, affected around 1% of queries, and has been the most recent of the Google Penguin algorithm updates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mustips.com/penguin-algorithm-the-real-time-update/ |title=Penguin Algorithm, The Real Time Update}}</ref>\n\nGoogle may have released Penguin 3.0 on October 18, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seroundtable.com/google-penguin-3-19313.html |title=Google Penguin 3.0 Likely Released Saturday Morning}}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 2014, Google's Pierre Farr confirmed that Penguin 3.0 was an algorithm \"refresh\", with no new signals added.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seroundtable.com/google-penguin-3-impact-roll-19321.html |title=Google AutoCorrects: Penguin 3.0 Still Rolling Out & 1% Impact}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2015, Google's John Mueller said in a Google+ hangout that both Penguin and Panda \"currently are not updating the data regularly\" and that updates must be pushed out manually. This confirms that the algorithm is not updated continuously which was believed to be the case earlier on in the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-says-the-penguin-panda-algorithms-still-require-manual-data-pushes-218212/|title=Penguin & Panda still require manual updates|author=Barry Schwartz|date=April 8, 2015|work=Search Engine Land|accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe strategic goal that Panda, Penguin, and the page layout update share is to display higher quality websites at the top of Google's [[Web search engine|search results]]. However, sites that were downranked as the result of these updates have different sets of characteristics. The main target of Google Penguin is [[spamdexing]] (including [[link bombing]]).{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nIn a Google+ Hangout on April 15, 2016, John Mueller said \"I am pretty sure when we start rolling out [Penguin] we will have a message to kind of post but at the moment I don't have anything specific to kind of announce.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webpronews.com/google-will-announce-long-anticipated-penguin-update-2016-04/|title=Google Will Announce The Long-Anticipated Penguin Update|date=2016-04-15|website=WebProNews|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005114749/https://www.webpronews.com/google-will-announce-long-anticipated-penguin-update-2016-04/|archive-date=October 5, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===  Penguin 4.0 (7th Penguin update) ===\nOn September 23, 2016 Google announced that Google Penguin was now part of the core algorithm<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-updates-penguin-says-now-real-time-part-core-algorithm-259302|title=Google updates Penguin, says it now runs in real time within the core search algorithm|date=2016-09-23|work=Search Engine Land|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en-US}}</ref> meaning that it updates in real time. Hence there will not longer be announcements by Google relating to future refreshes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://searchengineland.com/penguin-4-0-necessary-positive-improvement-261359|title=Penguin 4.0: Necessary and positive improvement|date=2016-10-25|work=Search Engine Land|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en-US}}</ref> Real-time also means that websites are evaluated in real-time and rankings impacted in real-time. During the last years webmasters instead always had to wait for the roll-out of the next update to get out of a Penguin penalty. Also, Google Penguin 4.0 is more granular as opposed to previous updates, since it may affect a website on a URL-basis as opposed to always affecting a whole website. Finally, Penguin 4.0 <ref name=\"searchengineland1\">{{Cite news|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-penguin-doesnt-penalize-bad-links-259981|title=Google Penguin doesn't penalize for bad links - or does it?|date=2016-09-28|work=Search Engine Land|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-penguin-looks-mostly-link-source-says-google-260902|title=Google Penguin looks mostly at your link source, says Google|date=2016-10-10|work=Search Engine Land|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en-US}}</ref> differs from previous Penguin versions since it does not demote a web site when it finds bad links. Instead it discounts the links, meaning it ignores them and they no longer count toward the website's ranking. As a result of this, there is less need to use the disavow file.<ref name=\"searchengineland1\"/> Google uses both algorithm and human reviewers to identify links that are unnatural (artificial), manipulative or deceptive and includes these in its Manual Actions report for websites.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manual Actions report|url=https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/2604824|accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Google's Penguin feedback form==\nTwo days after the Penguin update was released Google prepared a feedback form,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/viewform?formkey=dEVxdmdRWFJRTjRoLWZVTHZkaTBQbkE6MQ |title=Feedback on our recent algorithm update (\"Penguin\") |publisher=Docs.google.com |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2013}}</ref> designed for two categories of users: those who want to report [[web spam]] that still ranks highly after the [[search algorithm]] change, and those who think that their site got unfairly hit by the update. Google also has a reconsideration form through Google Webmaster Tools.\n\nIn January 2015, Google's John Mueller said that a Penguin penalty can be removed by simply building good links. The usual process is to remove bad links manually or by using Google's Disavow tool and then filing a reconsideration request. Mueller elaborated on this by saying the algorithm looks at the percentage of good links versus bad links, so by building more good links it may tip the algorithm in your favor which would lead to recovery.<ref>{{cite web|title = Google: Even Without Disavowing, Getting Good Links Can Remove Your Penguin Problems|url = https://www.seroundtable.com/google-disavow-good-links-penguin-19696.html|accessdate = 2015-06-25}}</ref>\n\n==Confirmed Penguin updates==\n\n* '''Penguin 1''' on April 24, 2012 (impacting around 3.1% of queries)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.fr/2012/04/another-step-to-reward-high-quality.html |title=Another step to reward high-quality sites |publisher=Official Google Blog |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 2''' on May 26, 2012 (impacting less than 0.1%)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/206232437427154944 |title=Google Releases Penguin Update 2 |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=May 26, 2012 |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 3''' on October 5, 2012 (impacting around 0.3% of queries)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/254335294063656960 |title=Google Penguin Update 3 Released |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=October 5, 2012 |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 4''' (also known as Penguin 2.0) on May 22, 2013 (impacting 2.3% of queries)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mattcutts.com/blog/penguin-2-0-rolled-out-today/ |title=Penguin 4, With Penguin 2.0 Generation Spam-Fighting |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=May 22, 2013 |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 5''' (also known as Penguin 2.1) on October 4, 2013 (impacting around 1% of queries)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/386231794883780609 |title=Penguin 5, With The Penguin 2.1 Spam-Filtering Algorithm |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=October 4, 2013 |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 6''' (also known as Penguin 3.0) on October 17, 2014 (impacting less than 1% English queries).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seroundtable.com/google-penguin-3-impact-roll-19321.html |title=Google AutoCorrects: Penguin 3.0 Still Rolling Out & 1% Impact |publisher=Barry Schwartz|date=October 21, 2014 |accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref>  On December 1, 2014 Google confirmed that the update was still rolling out with webmasters continuing to report significant fluctuations.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schwartz|first1=Barry|title=Google Penguin Reversals & Fluctuations This Morning|url=https://www.seroundtable.com/google-penguin-changes-19517.html|website=Search Engine Roundtable|publisher=SE  Roundtable|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 7''' (also known as Penguin 4.0) on September 23, 2016<ref>{{cite web|last1=Illyes|first1=Gary|title=Penguin is now part of our core algorithm|url=https://webmasters.googleblog.com/2016/09/penguin-is-now-part-of-our-core.html|website=Google Webmaster Central Blog|publisher=Google|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Google Panda]]\n* [[Google penalty]]\n* [[Google Hummingbird]]\n* [[RankBrain]]\n* [[Author Rank]]\n* [[Mobilegeddon]]\n* [[PageRank]]\n* [[Google Pigeon]]\n* [[Knowledge Graph]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303505504577406751747002494 Wall Street Journal - As Google Tweaks Searches, Some Get Lost in the Web]\n* [http://www.weareinfront.com/google-penguin-update-guide/ In Front Digital - A Guide To The Penguin Update]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20171005114749/https://www.webpronews.com/google-will-announce-long-anticipated-penguin-update-2016-04/ WebProNews - Google To Announce The Latest Penguin Update]\n* [http://www.abac-bd.com/google-penguin-3-0-update-rolling-out-effects-and-cure/ Google Penguin 3.0 Update Rolling Out, Effects and Cure]\n* [https://digitrio.com.sg/the-return-of-the-penguin/ Google Penguin 4.0 Star Wars Infographics]\n* [https://makeyourrank.in/news/google-seo-updates-privacy-policy/ Google privacy policy updates]\n{{Google LLC}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Search engine optimization]]\n[[Category:Link analysis]]\n[[Category:Google Search|Penguin]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Google search engine algorithm update}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2014}}\n'''Google Penguin''' is a [[codename]]<ref name=SEL>{{cite web|author=Matt Cutts |url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/206232437427154944 |title=Penguin Gets Official Name |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref> for a Google algorithm update that was first announced on April 24, 2012. The update was aimed at decreasing [[Search engine optimization|search engine rankings]] of websites that violate Google's Webmaster Guidelines<ref>{{cite web|url=https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/35769#3|title=Webmaster Guidelines - Webmaster Tools Help|publisher=Support.google.com|accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref> by using now declared [[black-hat SEO]] techniques involved in increasing artificially the ranking of a webpage by manipulating the number of links pointing to the page. Such tactics are commonly described as link schemes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://support.google.com/webmasters/bin/answer.py?answer=66356 |title=Link schemes - Webmaster Tools Help |publisher=Support.google.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref> According to Google's John Mueller,<ref name=\"SEL\" /> Google has announced all updates to the Penguin filter to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://searchengineland.com/no-google-hasnt-released-unannounced-peguin-updates-149156|title=No, Google Hasn't Released Unannounced Penguin Updates|author=Barry Schwartz|date=February 20, 2013|accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Effect on search results==\nBy Google's estimates,<ref name=GBlog>http://insidesearch.blogspot.com/2012/04/another-step-to-reward-high-quality.html</ref> Penguin affects approximately 3.1% of [[Web search query|search queries]] in [[English language|English]], about 3% of queries in languages like [[German language|German]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], and [[Arabic]], and an even greater percentage of them in \"highly spammed\" languages. On May 25, 2012, Google unveiled another Penguin update, called Penguin 1.1. This update, according to [[Matt Cutts]], former head of webspam at Google, was supposed to affect less than one-tenth of a percent of English searches. The guiding principle for the update was to penalize websites that were using manipulative techniques to achieve high rankings. Pre-Penguin sites commonly used negative link building techniques to rank highly and get traffic, once Penguin was rolled out it meant that content was key and those with great content would be recognised and those with little or spammy content would be penalised and receive no ranking benefits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weareinfront.com/google-penguin-update-guide/|title=A Guide To The Penguin Update - In Front Digital|date=2015-03-12|website=In Front Digital|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref> The purpose per Google was to catch excessive spammers. Allegedly, few websites lost search rankings on Google for specific keywords during the [[Google Panda|Panda]] and Penguin rollouts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seroundtable.com/penguin-traffic-drop-chart-15096.html|title=Here Is What It Looks Like To Be Hit By Google Penguin|website=seroundtable.com|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref> Google specifically mentions that [[doorway page]]s, which are only built to attract search engine traffic, are against their webmaster guidelines.\n\nIn January 2012, the so-called Page Layout Algorithm Update<ref>{{cite web|url=http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2012/01/page-layout-algorithm-improvement.html |title=Official Google Webmaster Central Blog: Page layout algorithm improvement |publisher=Googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com |date=2012-01-19 |accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref> (also known as the Top Heavy Update)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://searchengineland.com/google-updates-page-layout-algorithm-go-sites-top-heavy-ads-183929|title=Google Updates Its Page Layout Algorithm To Go After Sites \"Top Heavy\" With Ads|date=February 10, 2014|publisher=SearchEngineLand.com|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> was released, which targeted websites with too many ads, or too little content [[above the fold]].\n\nPenguin 3 was released October 5, 2012 and affected 0.3% of queries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/254335294063656960 |title=Google Penguin Update 3 Released, Impacts 0.3% Of English-Language Queries |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=October 5, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2013}}</ref> Penguin 4 (also known as Penguin 2.0) was released on May 22, 2013 and affected 2.3% of queries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mattcutts.com/blog/penguin-2-0-rolled-out-today/ |title=Penguin 4, With Penguin 2.0 Generation Spam-Fighting |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=May 22, 2013 |accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> Penguin 5 (also known as Penguin 2.1)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/386231794883780609 |title=The Penguin 2.1 Spam-Filtering Algorithm |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=October 4, 2013 |accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> was released on October 4, 2013, affected around 1% of queries, and has been the most recent of the Google Penguin algorithm updates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mustips.com/penguin-algorithm-the-real-time-update/ |title=Penguin Algorithm, The Real Time Update}}</ref>\n\nGoogle may have released Penguin 3.0 on October 18, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seroundtable.com/google-penguin-3-19313.html |title=Google Penguin 3.0 Likely Released Saturday Morning}}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 2014, Google's Pierre Farr confirmed that Penguin 3.0 was an algorithm \"refresh\", with no new signals added.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seroundtable.com/google-penguin-3-impact-roll-19321.html |title=Google AutoCorrects: Penguin 3.0 Still Rolling Out & 1% Impact}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2015, Google's John Mueller said in a Google+ hangout that both Penguin and Panda \"currently are not updating the data regularly\" and that updates must be pushed out manually. This confirms that the algorithm is not updated continuously which was believed to be the case earlier on in the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-says-the-penguin-panda-algorithms-still-require-manual-data-pushes-218212/|title=Penguin & Panda still require manual updates|author=Barry Schwartz|date=April 8, 2015|work=Search Engine Land|accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe strategic goal that Panda, Penguin, and the page layout update share is to display higher quality websites at the top of Google's [[Web search engine|search results]]. However, sites that were downranked as the result of these updates have different sets of characteristics. The main target of Google Penguin is [[spamdexing]] (including [[link bombing]]).{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nIn a Google+ Hangout on April 15, 2016, John Mueller said \"I am pretty sure when we start rolling out [Penguin] we will have a message to kind of post but at the moment I don't have anything specific to kind of announce.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webpronews.com/google-will-announce-long-anticipated-penguin-update-2016-04/|title=Google Will Announce The Long-Anticipated Penguin Update|date=2016-04-15|website=WebProNews|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005114749/https://www.webpronews.com/google-will-announce-long-anticipated-penguin-update-2016-04/|archive-date=October 5, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===  Penguin 4.0 (7th Penguin update) ===\nOn September 23, 2016 Google announced that Google Penguin was now part of the core algorithm<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-updates-penguin-says-now-real-time-part-core-algorithm-259302|title=Google updates Penguin, says it now runs in real time within the core search algorithm|date=2016-09-23|work=Search Engine Land|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en-US}}</ref> meaning that it updates in real time. Hence there will not longer be announcements by Google relating to future refreshes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://searchengineland.com/penguin-4-0-necessary-positive-improvement-261359|title=Penguin 4.0: Necessary and positive improvement|date=2016-10-25|work=Search Engine Land|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en-US}}</ref> Real-time also means that websites are evaluated in real-time and rankings impacted in real-time. During the last years webmasters instead always had to wait for the roll-out of the next update to get out of a Penguin penalty. Also, Google Penguin 4.0 is more granular as opposed to previous updates, since it may affect a website on a URL-basis as opposed to always affecting a whole website. Finally, Penguin 4.0 <ref name=\"searchengineland1\">{{Cite news|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-penguin-doesnt-penalize-bad-links-259981|title=Google Penguin doesn't penalize for bad links - or does it?|date=2016-09-28|work=Search Engine Land|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-penguin-looks-mostly-link-source-says-google-260902|title=Google Penguin looks mostly at your link source, says Google|date=2016-10-10|work=Search Engine Land|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en-US}}</ref> differs from previous Penguin versions since it does not demote a web site when it finds bad links. Instead it discounts the links, meaning it ignores them and they no longer count toward the website's ranking. As a result of this, there is less need to use the disavow file.<ref name=\"searchengineland1\"/> Google uses both algorithm and human reviewers to identify links that are unnatural (artificial), manipulative or deceptive and includes these in its Manual Actions report for websites.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manual Actions report|url=https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/2604824|accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Google's Penguin feedback form==\nTwo days after the Penguin update was released Google prepared a feedback form,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/viewform?formkey=dEVxdmdRWFJRTjRoLWZVTHZkaTBQbkE6MQ |title=Feedback on our recent algorithm update (\"Penguin\") |publisher=Docs.google.com |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=June 16, 2013}}</ref> designed for two categories of users: those who want to report [[web spam]] that still ranks highly after the [[search algorithm]] change, and those who think that their site got unfairly hit by the update. Google also has a reconsideration form through Google Webmaster Tools.\n\nIn January 2015, Google's John Mueller said that a Penguin penalty can be removed by simply building good links. The usual process is to remove bad links manually or by using Google's Disavow tool and then filing a reconsideration request. Mueller elaborated on this by saying the algorithm looks at the percentage of good links versus bad links, so by building more good links it may tip the algorithm in your favor which would lead to recovery.<ref>{{cite web|title = Google: Even Without Disavowing, Getting Good Links Can Remove Your Penguin Problems|url = https://www.seroundtable.com/google-disavow-good-links-penguin-19696.html|accessdate = 2015-06-25}}</ref>\n\n==Confirmed Penguin updates==\n\n* '''Penguin 1''' on April 24, 2012 (impacting around 3.1% of queries)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.fr/2012/04/another-step-to-reward-high-quality.html |title=Another step to reward high-quality sites |publisher=Official Google Blog |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 2''' on May 26, 2012 (impacting less than 0.1%)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/206232437427154944 |title=Google Releases Penguin Update 2 |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=May 26, 2012 |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 3''' on October 5, 2012 (impacting around 0.3% of queries)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/254335294063656960 |title=Google Penguin Update 3 Released |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=October 5, 2012 |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 4''' (also known as Penguin 2.0) on May 22, 2013 (impacting 2.3% of queries)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mattcutts.com/blog/penguin-2-0-rolled-out-today/ |title=Penguin 4, With Penguin 2.0 Generation Spam-Fighting |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=May 22, 2013 |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 5''' (also known as Penguin 2.1) on October 4, 2013 (impacting around 1% of queries)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mattcutts/status/386231794883780609 |title=Penguin 5, With The Penguin 2.1 Spam-Filtering Algorithm |publisher=Matt Cutts |date=October 4, 2013 |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 6''' (also known as Penguin 3.0) on October 17, 2014 (impacting less than 1% English queries).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seroundtable.com/google-penguin-3-impact-roll-19321.html |title=Google AutoCorrects: Penguin 3.0 Still Rolling Out & 1% Impact |publisher=Barry Schwartz|date=October 21, 2014 |accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref>  On December 1, 2014 Google confirmed that the update was still rolling out with webmasters continuing to report significant fluctuations.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schwartz|first1=Barry|title=Google Penguin Reversals & Fluctuations This Morning|url=https://www.seroundtable.com/google-penguin-changes-19517.html|website=Search Engine Roundtable|publisher=SE  Roundtable|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Penguin 7''' (also known as Penguin 4.0) on September 23, 2016<ref>{{cite web|last1=Illyes|first1=Gary|title=Penguin is now part of our core algorithm|url=https://webmasters.googleblog.com/2016/09/penguin-is-now-part-of-our-core.html|website=Google Webmaster Central Blog|publisher=Google|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Google Panda]]\n* [[Google penalty]]\n* [[Google Hummingbird]]\n* [[RankBrain]]\n* [[Author Rank]]\n* [[Mobilegeddon]]\n* [[PageRank]]\n* [[Google Pigeon]]\n* [[Knowledge Graph]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303505504577406751747002494 Wall Street Journal - As Google Tweaks Searches, Some Get Lost in the Web]\n* [http://www.weareinfront.com/google-penguin-update-guide/ In Front Digital - A Guide To The Penguin Update]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20171005114749/https://www.webpronews.com/google-will-announce-long-anticipated-penguin-update-2016-04/ WebProNews - Google To Announce The Latest Penguin Update]\n* [http://www.abac-bd.com/google-penguin-3-0-update-rolling-out-effects-and-cure/ Google Penguin 3.0 Update Rolling Out, Effects and Cure]\n* [https://digitrio.com.sg/the-return-of-the-penguin/ Google Penguin 4.0 Star Wars Infographics]\n\n{{Google LLC}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Search engine optimization]]\n[[Category:Link analysis]]\n[[Category:Google Search|Penguin]]\n", "name_user": "Makeyourrank", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Penguin"}
{"title_page": "List of UNIVAC products", "text_new": "This is a '''list of [[UNIVAC]] products'''. It ends in 1986, the year that [[Sperry Corporation]] merged with [[Burroughs Corporation]] - after a second more hostile and well-documented takeover attempt mounted by Burrough's CEO W. Michael Blumenthal, which was given the green-light by Ronald Reagan and was funded by massive loans from the banks - to form [[Unisys]].\n\nA lot of the text here is ambiguous or wrong.\n\n== The Remington Rand years (1950 to 1955) ==\n\n=== Calculating devices ===\n*[[UNIVAC 60]]\n*[[UNIVAC 120]]\n*[[UNIVAC 121]]\n\n===Computer systems===\n*[[UNIVAC I]]\n*[[UNIVAC III]]\n*[[UNIVAC 1101]]\n*[[UNIVAC 1102]]\n*[[UNIVAC 1103]]\n*[[UNIVAC 1104]]\n*[[UNIVAC Solid State]]<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/bitsavers_univacussS_572718/SolidState90_Specs USS 90 Specification Features by Remington Rand Univac]</ref>\n\n===Peripherals===\n\n====Storage====\n* [[UNISERVO]] [[tape drive]]\n\n====Display and print====\n*[[UNIVAC High speed printer]] 600 line/min printer\n\n===Offline tape handling units===\n*[[UNIPRINTER]] 10 char/s [[Computer printer|printer]] with tape drive\n*[[UNITYPER]] keyboard with tape drive\n*[[UNIVAC Tape to Card converter]] card punch with tape drive\n*[[UNIVAC Card to Tape converter]] card reader with tape drive\n*[[UNIVAC Paper Tape to Tape converter]] [[paper tape]] reader with tape drive\n\n== The Sperry Rand years (1955 to 1978) ==\n\n===Calculating devices===\n*[[UNIVAC 1004]]\n*[[UNIVAC 1005]]\n\n===Computer systems===\n\n====Embedded systems====\n*[[AN/USQ-17]] &ndash; the [[Naval Tactical Data System]] (NTDS) or M-460\n*[[AN/USQ-20]] &ndash; updated NTDS, aka UNIVAC 1206 or G-40\n*[[AN/UYK-7]] &ndash; multiprocessor for [[Aegis]]. 32-bit replacement for the [[Naval Tactical Data System]], derived from [[UNIVAC 1108]]\n*[[AN/UYK-8]] &ndash; dual processor version of the [[Naval Tactical Data System]]\n*[[AN/UYK-20]]\n*[[AN/UYK-43]] &ndash; replaced and shared its instruction set with the AN/UYK-7\n*[[AN/UYK-44]] &ndash; replaced and shared its instruction set with the AN/UYK-20\n*[[UNIVAC 1218]] &ndash; real time computer\n*[[UNIVAC 1230]] &ndash; later, faster (2&times;) version of the AN/USQ-20 (memory size and I/O were identical)\n\n====Word machines====\n*[[UNIVAC LARC|LARC]]\n*[[UNIVAC Solid State]]\n*[[UNIVAC II]]\n*[[UNIVAC III]]\n*[[UNIVAC 418]] &ndash; real time computer\n*[[UNIVAC 418-II]] &ndash; real time computer\n*[[UNIVAC 418-III]] &ndash; real time computer\n*UNIVAC 422<ref>\n*{{cite web |title=J. Presper Eckert and Pat Boone in front of Univac 422 {{!}} 102633139 {{!}} Computer History Museum |url=http://www.computerhistory.org/collections/catalog/102633139 |website=www.computerhistory.org |language=en |access-date=2018-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920195627/http://www.computerhistory.org/collections/catalog/102633139 |archive-date=2018-09-20 |dead-url=no |df= }}\n*{{cite web |last1=Bowie |first1=Stephen |title=The monoliths: 17 supercomputers from the \u201960s |url=https://aux.avclub.com/the-monoliths-17-supercomputers-from-the-60s-1798269311 |website=AUX |at=11. Technical Electronic Amplifier Code Handler (TEACH), The Patty Duke Show: \u201cThe Genius\u201d (1963) |access-date=2018-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920195816/https://aux.avclub.com/the-monoliths-17-supercomputers-from-the-60s-1798269311 |archive-date=2018-09-20 |dead-url=no |df= }} Contains link to video of the computer</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UNIVAC 422 |url=https://www.smecc.org/univac_422.htm |website=www.smecc.org |access-date=2018-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627230139/http://smecc.org/univac_422.htm |archive-date=2017-06-27 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ed-thelen.org/comp-hist/BRL64-u.html#UNIVAC-422-TRNG-COMP|title=UNIVAC 422 TRNG COMP|last=Weik|first=Martin H.|date=Jan 1964|website=ed-thelen.org|series=A Fourth Survey of Domestic Electronic Digital Computing Systems|access-date=2018-09-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523210121/http://ed-thelen.org/comp-hist/BRL64-u.html#UNIVAC-422-TRNG-COMP|archive-date=2018-05-23|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> - Univac Digital Trainer,<ref>{{cite web |last1=K |first1=Special |title=Apollo Guidance Computer (AGC) - fly me to the Moon |url=http://kelloggserialreports.blogspot.com/2008/10/apollo-guidance-computer-agc-fly-me-to.html |website=TO THE MOON, MARS, AND BEYOND |date=1 October 2008 |access-date=2018-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920195643/http://kelloggserialreports.blogspot.com/2008/10/apollo-guidance-computer-agc-fly-me-to.html |archive-date=2018-09-20 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ed-thelen.org/comp-hist/BRL64-u.html#UNIVAC-DIG-TRNR|title=UNIVAC DIG TRNR|last=Weik|first=Martin H.|date=Jan 1964|website=ed-thelen.org|series=A Fourth Survey of Domestic Electronic Digital Computing Systems|access-date=2018-09-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523210121/http://ed-thelen.org/comp-hist/BRL64-u.html#UNIVAC-DIG-TRNR|archive-date=2018-05-23|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> part of the Programmed Educational Package (Prep)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Haga |first1=Enoch J. |title=Understanding Automation: PREP FOR COMPUTER TRAINING |journal=The Journal of Business Education |date=November 1962 |volume=38 |issue=2 |page=70 |doi=10.1080/08832323.1962.10116580 |url=https://doi.org/10.1080/08832323.1962.10116580 |language=en |issn=0021-9444}}</ref>\n*[[UNIVAC 490]] &ndash; commercial adaptation of AN/USQ real-time system\n*[[UNIVAC 492]]\n*[[UNIVAC 494]]\n*[[UNIVAC 494-MAPS]] &ndash; The first Multi-Associated Processor System - not made available commercially\n*[[UNIVAC 1103A]]\n*[[UNIVAC 1104]]\n*[[UNIVAC 1105]]\n*[[UNIVAC 1100/2200 series]]:\n:*[[UNIVAC 1106]] (half-speed [[UNIVAC 1108|1108]])\n:*[[UNIVAC 1107]]\n:*[[UNIVAC 1108]]\n:*[[UNIVAC 1110]]\n:*[[UNIVAC 1100/2200 series#Semiconductor memory series|UNIVAC 1100/10]] (1106 upgraded with semiconductor memory)\n:*[[UNIVAC 1100/2200 series#Semiconductor memory series|UNIVAC 1100/20]] (1108 upgraded with semiconductor memory)\n:*[[UNIVAC 1100/2200 series#Semiconductor memory series|UNIVAC 1100/40]] (1110 upgraded with semiconductor memory)\n:*[[UNIVAC 1100/82A]]\n:*[[UNIVAC 1100/181]]\n\n====Variable word length machines====\n*[[UNIVAC 1050]]\n\n====Byte machines====\nThese machines implemented a variant of the [[IBM System/360]] architecture\n*[[UNIVAC 9000 series]]\n**UNIVAC 9200\n**UNIVAC 9300\n**UNIVAC 9400\n**UNIVAC 9480\n\n===Peripherals===\n\n====Storage====\n*FH-432 (Flying Head) drum\n*FH-880 (Flying Head) drum\n*FH-1782 (Flying Head) drum\n*[[FASTRAND]] drum drive\n*[[RANDEX]] drum drive<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.computer.org/csdl/proceedings/afips/1960/5057/00/50570189.pdf |title={title} |access-date=2018-05-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180513224210/https://www.computer.org/csdl/proceedings/afips/1960/5057/00/50570189.pdf |archive-date=2018-05-13 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref>\n*[[UNISERVO I]] tape drive\n*[[UNISERVO II]] tape drive\n*[[UNISERVO IIA]] tape drive\n*[[UNISERVO III]] tape drive\n*[[UNISERVO IIIC]] tape drive\n*[[UNISERVO VI-C]] tape drive\n*[[UNISERVO VIII-C]] tape drive\n*[[UNISERVO 12]] tape drive (1600 BPI)\n*[[UNISERVO 16]] tape drive (1600 BPI)\n*[[UNISERVO 20]] tape drive (1600 BPI)\n*[[UNISERVO 30-36]] tape drives (6250BPI)(OEM from STK)\n\n====Display and print====\n*[[Uniscope]]\n\n====Communication====\n*[[UNIVAC BP]] - Buffer Processor; used as communications front-end to 418 and 490\n*UNIVAC CTMC - Communications Terminal Module Controller\n*UNIVAC GCS - General Communications System\n\n===Software===\n\n====Operating systems and system software====\n* [[BOSS III]] or '''B'''usiness '''O'''riented '''S'''ystems '''S'''upervisor was the operating system for the UNIVAC III\n* [[EXEC I]]\n* [[EXEC II]]\n* [[EXEC 8]]\n\n====Utilities, languages, and development aids=